However, we assume that this is Higgs, because the chances of being wrong seem few, we will see what this is about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to violate that standard and do not try too much, because it will end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the principle of Pauli exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" which is largely composed of some of its characteristics.
Physicians classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called farmers, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories, which is indeed extraordinary, the bosones are divided into two groups: the months, of which we will not speak here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the boson of Higgs would be somehow related.
These bosons, you might stress here, they're not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as an "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" there is an electromagnetic wave (from light, from infrared, from ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the boson "force carriers".
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is about another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a little as if it were an frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
That is why a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN (the great hadron collider is a 27 km circle ring!) is needed to achieve such energy levels.
