But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositors of accounting books, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins changes consist of the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a sort of interim central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file segmentation, i.e. transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "trace" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the one-hundredth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculation power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The mistake used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money-laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same defect.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject such payments.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from Weizmann Incite in Israel, analyzed the accounting book and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "giant basses" were launched.
"Three thousand dollars have been changed," Jon Holmquist rejoices, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a textbook on that currency, believes quite in the potential of this technology as well as in the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a non-contact mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain in anonymity.
The system is easy to set up in businesses, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", needs Pierre Noizat, who ensures that it has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to be imposed, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, today considered high, if this currency is successful.
