As deputies and human rights defenders discuss the implications of the law on compulsory examination, they have already appeared in the country where they trade in "false" certificates.
Each year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Its only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
Since 1 December a law enters into force, according to which each migrant worker must carry out an examination to check his or her knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, in time, as promised in the Federal Immigration Service, examinations will be made mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be sufficient to carry out the examination of the language, but also of Russian history and the basis of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
The exception is for citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who obtained their certificates of education and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 shall not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will be sponsored by the Russian Language Institute Pushkin, the University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the State University of St. Petersburg and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants can be tested in all cities, now in Russia more than 160 such centres are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the review was supported by state officials and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, often managed to ask the press this question: What will this really bring?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language, both for Russians and immigrants themselves, bring?
First, the representatives of the Immigration Service respond, which will reduce the number of people suffering from "labour slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labour immigrants, explains Víctor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defence of their rights must begin before departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of the cases.
Problems are experienced by immigrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language or go through medical control.
Without the understanding of the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, on the pretext of helping, put a "paying trip" on a creepy and narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working from 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received a number of complaints from our immigrants.
"They are promised something in their homeland, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages," confirms the head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Tajikistan Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get angry, Chief!
In the meantime, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to work in Russia recognize that they do not only know the language of the country they want to go to, but also write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmen, Uzbek, Tayikos who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families don't even have anything to feed their children, because they don't talk about dressing them up, wearing them and buying them what they need for school.
When they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, with regard to the language law, rights defenders point to an important point.
The examinations will be carried out only for immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbid the passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not that easy.
The cause is in bureaucratic obstacles and language difficulties themselves.
Moreover, legalization costs money: twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only a thousand five hundred rubles.
