Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with one another.
The cause is in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with the unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (of wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to that end "proves a drop" of the competitor's price in order to be made with most of the market and thus increase its profit margin.
On a large scale, it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the labour price, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment caused by this phenomenon, the social expenditure of the state necessarily grows.
This whole situation is conducive to the total disinterest of employers for paying taxes and compensation for the economic and social damage they have caused in their pursuit of benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that there is no need to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations in certain economies where the Governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thereby attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments make private capital available to their own population without regard to the social decline.
This is particularly evident in the changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the private capital dictatorship, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees to labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is already about a million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly common case: people employed with such low wages that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
