The saving measures of almost all the southern states of the EU undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abismal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live with a gross wage at the limit of society, hoping that one day they will reach the private investor capital country.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, poverty then moves from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian and African continue to work for a small part of a European salary.
This also affects all Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm to the satisfaction that the state should not bring capital to the economy, which would lead the economy to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by getting involved in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence its selfishness in the political process and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
The situation in Germany is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, are responsible for drafting bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that the liberal-oriented democracies quickly find themselves in a situation such as that described by Appianos in his work The crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had been breaking up and the administrations were busy with force."
In exchange for bribes, ill-gotten favors and help finance stones or swords.
