The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that today's society is based on disregarded preferences of the individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is unable, in its essence, to understand and claim the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as that of then, a decline of the unprecedented elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next blow.
The really devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian disasters we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the law on public procurement is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the Czech Republic government will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
