Nobody likes to go to those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom city located at the gates of Rotterdam which hardly deserves a fleeting visit, has the dubious honour of having stood with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute somehow to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that is how the political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, an entire master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings that are paired with cynics, took the theme with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and clung to shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellows:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, the so-called `Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros rises at the expected location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is complemented by underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and town buildings.
In early November, the book mount was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking history, which so far had nothing but to offer that a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather enter a dairy center, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in his history.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese maker.
It is true that there is an elevator that carries us right to the center of this massive mountain, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather merge with their topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor collected and the elegant lighthouses unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
Upon raising the view you can see the park banks, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And all over books, books, and more books.
"Usually the book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put up the classic spatial configuration and remove the reading area from the inside outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education centre and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and barandilla at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers increasingly shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the city of Spijkenisse.
And this is how one day, on an agricultural farm in Frisian, we meet the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of few millimetres of thickness has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is cheap and efficient.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library this tissue was first taken in such quantities until it obtained plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells of a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of nearly 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the café you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquetas and their figus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment at the same time that keeps the atmospheric humidity suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
