Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the special relationship between the country and Israel, Germany should be careful.
But at the same time, I do not think that it supports the US position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it concerned establishing a flight ban zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because he is currently reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a leading policy, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still testing what their role will be, but they've already started the road towards a "normal" foreign policy.
A similar foreign policy to countries such as France and Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy specifically mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is ready to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
