German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Near East, especially in the Gulf.
That is why it must be careful and not alienate from Arab public opinion or from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it so much importance as it is not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by refraining from voting in important decisions such as in the Palestinian vote?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German stance has a huge degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic break-up as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has managed to achieve a certain degree of respect.
After all, all of this has only been done to show that it is a country to which they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the U.S. has clearly been in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American internal policy.
I believe that the Obama government is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot defend that position in public.
