Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, as prosecutors claim.
Prosecutors are trying to deal with Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse during his stay in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period in Quantico military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leak of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now claimed he suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation that the prosecution conducted to Manning in a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of the weekly visits of officers of the unit that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing carried out following the defence's request to dismiss the case as its imprisonment had been hard and that this had already claimed enough punishment, arrived one day after Manning had testified that he had thought of suicide while he was under arrest.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In the view of Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at the Quantico military prison, where he was imprisoned on a maximum prison basis from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted their answers.
When Friday Fein asked about the forms, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given him by the concealers as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about certain issues and that the officers visiting him had talked about those problems and had indicated that they would be treated, but that they had not left a record of those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidence' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I didn't mention any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Denise Lind Army, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a council to examine the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was found.
The military said that they had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is below the level of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure their protection and safety for others.
"I wanted the older state to know that I was okay and (I wanted to) stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Navy base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning stated that once moved to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a hemp, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming out pointing to his eyes while he was asleep.
He said that if the janitors couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on the treatment Manning received.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in his statement on Thursday, according to which, after having been forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced to stand naked in front of the lockers and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the counting.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said that he deduced by the order given to him by the locker that should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his hemp to self-injury but that he had not.
Manning testified that night they had taken off his cell his underwear, his chanchlas and his glasses.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he spent during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted on the war council, which is expected to start early next year.
The defence stated that it plans to have Manning found guilty of minor crimes and to defend other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has claimed that Manning was detained in accordance with the rules of application for all detainees who are in maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully provoking the publication of information on the Internet, filtering information from the national defence and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
