But more and more scholars and experts in child development praise the goodness of boredom.
According to them, it is good that, both us and our children, we get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in a good spirit?
Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, it was assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, says, and author of the book "Boredom: A Livey History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press, it is not.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
In the walls of Pompey there are graffiti in Latin about the boredom that dates back to the first century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many ways," says John D. Eastwood, professor of Psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the research published and presenting the idea to a panel of discussion consisting of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desiring, but unable, to participate in an activity that fills you."
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do anything but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the care process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
Boring can sound awfully like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed feel that they have the problem.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Uninvolved Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which the participants heard a tape from a person who read the article of a magazine.
Some groups heard in the next room a TV program on every volume that kept no relationship, others listened to it with the low volume, so that it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the low volume program showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the alteration of attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, professor of Neuroscience at Guelph University, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective pieces on a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not get bored."
"In fact, we currently know that moving or doing garabads, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help to fight it, as they make that person physically more alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to remain still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a film that is particularly boring.
But some people tend to get more bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers in the 1980s developed a "flight trend scale."
The scale includes issues such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things I'm interested in that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of Psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using these scales, researchers have discovered that boys tend to get more bored than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and their parents between seven and eight times a day through a search.
He discovered that 32 percent of adolescents said he would get bored while he was at school or doing his homework, while 23 percent said he would get bored when he was not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they'd get bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest quotas," largely because both children and adolescents are not given great control over what they want to do.
So, coming back to my question from the beginning: is it good to bore?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into substance consumption as a method of combating it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"The boredom is the way your brain has to tell you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to do so," says Professor Fenske.
And "this ability to do so applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself but learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But neither should we be too critical of him.
Our objective should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our way of seeing, we need to bore ourselves more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate to something worth it," he says.
Notice that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it is difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
